location.city_name: Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe

social_posts.post_text:
“The Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe”, 

a vast expanse of concrete slabs designed by architect Peter Eisenman, stands as a poignant tribute to the millions of lives lost during the Holocaust. 

As you wander through the undulating landscape of this solemn monument, the shifting perspectives and shadows evoke a sense of disorientation, mirroring the emotional turmoil of history. Urging us to honor and remember those whose stories remain forever etched in time. 

Eisenman’s thought-provoking creation serves as both a powerful reminder of a somber past and a testament to human resilience. Lest we forget

DIGITAL SCRAPBOOK EP.1 (5 pages)

this was a very fun project to come up with and work on! I started by taking photos on my broken point n shoot…

I printed them out, wrote on them, and scanned them back in with other objects from my time in nyc.

Using artificial intelligence, I generated an expanded version of a drawing I made to use as a background for the project.

I’ve seen digital scrapbooks before, but I wanted to add my own touch using videos!! What do you think?

#digitalscrapbook #bemor

i love life so much i ruin it for myself...

i feel like i care deeply about life and how i spend my time. to the point that i’m always crippled by anxiety of trying to “make the best decision.”

i’m 20 but i feel so overly conscious of my mortality...

i feel an obsessive need to inject every experience and soak up every feeling, right into my brain.

life is so short… so i feel the need to take in as much of it as possible.

an anxiety that doesn’t go away no matter the circumstance.

i often feel like i’m not doing enough or that what i do isn’t good enough...

to the point that i can’t even be present, limiting my ability to feel grateful and enjoy my life…

you swim when you don’t notice… but when you worry about the water, you drown.

- brain dump 02.03.2023

Yesterday I had my first data art installation put up…

Using python code, I extrapolated the color data of this video I made a couple months ago into a csv file. 

With this csv file data set I then used python code again to represent the color distribution of the pixels in every frame.

On the top right is a downsampled 3D point map of the pixels and their colors. On the bottom right is a heat map of each frames “color profile”. 

On the left, it’s just a visual representation using traditional graphs.

Behind every video or piece of digital art… there is data. 

Why not show that?

this is a beautiful train ride from New York City to Vermont. I love the way that shadows are cast from the trees into the train. I was hypnotized the entire train ride and did my best to capture the experience. I feel like when beauty is in the most things… it is the most beautiful. Something about common experience being beautiful is quite interesting to me. But I particularly love the way that light dances on a train.
